NoteProblem A1, 2024 Putnam Mathematical Competition



Determine all positive integers \(n\) for which there exist positive integers \(a,b,c\) such that \[2a^n+3b^n=4c^n.\]


For \(n=1\) there are infinitely many solutions; one family of solutions is given by \(a=t\in \ZZ^+\), \(b=2t\), \(c=2t\).
Let \(n&gt;1\). By rearranging to \[3b^n=4c^n-2a^n=2(2c^n-a^n),\] we see that \(b\) must be even. Thus, we must have \(b=2\beta\) for some \(\beta\in \ZZ^+,\) and we have reduced solving the original equation to solving the equation \[2a^n+3\cdot2^n\beta^n=4c^n.\] Rearranging again and using that \(n&gt;1\) (and therefore \(n-2\geq 0\)), we find that \[2a^n=4(2c^n-3\cdot2^{n-2}\beta^n),\] so we conclude that \(a\) is also even. Writing \(a=2\alpha\), our equation becomes \[(1)\text{ }\text{ }\text{ }2^{n+1}\alpha^n+3\cdot 2^n+\beta^n=4c^n.\]
From here we consider two cases: (i) \(n=2\) and (ii) \(n&gt;2\).

If \(n=2\) then (1) reduces to \[(2)\text{ }\text{ }\text{ }2\alpha^2+3\beta^2=c^2\] after dividing by 4 on both sides. We see that \(2\alpha^2\equiv c^2\mod 3\); since \(\{0,1\}\) are the quadratic residues mod 3, it follows that \(\alpha=3A\) and \(c=3C\) for some \(A,B\). Substituting this into (2), we get \[\begin{align} 18A^2+3\beta^2=9C^2.\end{align}\] Rearranging to \(3\beta^2=9(C^2-2A^2)\) shows that \(\beta=3B\) for some \(B\). Substituting this into (3) gives \[18A^2+27B^2=9C^2,\] which reduces to \[2A^2+3B^2=C^2\] after dividing by 9 on both sides. Thus, if \((\alpha,\beta,c)\) is a solution to (2) then so is \((\alpha/3,\beta/3,c/3)\), and we conclude that no solution exists by infinite descent.
If \(n&gt;2\) then \(2^n&gt;4\) and we must have that \(c=2\gamma\) for some \(\gamma\in \ZZ^+\); substituting into (1) gives \[2^{n+1}\alpha^n+3\cdot2^n\beta^n=4\cdot 2^n\gamma^n.\] After dividing by \(2^n\) on both sides, we get that \(2\alpha^n+3\beta^n=4\gamma^n\). Thus, if \((a,b,c)\) solves the equation from the problem statement then so does \((a/3,b/3,c/3),\) and we conclude that no solution exists by infinite descent.

